## Non-Obvious Design Decisions

### No persistent mapped buffers
Every `Flush` batch call maps the GPU buffer with `D3D11_MAP_WRITE_DISCARD`, copies from the CPU array, and immediately unmaps. The CPU `BatchData` arrays in `RendererDataSingletonComponent` are the real persistent store; the GPU buffers are re-uploaded every frame.

### `BATCH_MAX_COUNT` is a hard limit for layer batches
`DrawLayerBatch` uses `PG_CORE_EXCEPT` (exception, not assert) when the batch exceeds `BATCH_MAX_COUNT * QUAD_INDEX_COUNT`. The non-layer `DrawBatch` auto-flushes recursively, but `DrawLayerBatch` does not — layer ordering requires collecting all draws before submitting.

### Layer encoded in Z component of transform
`DrawLayerBatch` extracts the layer index directly from `transform[3][2]` (the translation-Z) and then zeroes it before building vertex positions. This means callers must encode their draw layer as the Z translation of the transform matrix.

### Both batch maps coexist
`m_BatchMap` (non-layered) and `m_LayerBatchMap` (layered) are flushed independently. The non-layered map is flushed first, then layered draws 0–99. This means any draw routed to `m_BatchMap` always renders before any layered draw regardless of texture or order.

### Constant buffers allocated per uniform upload
`Dx11Shader::UploadUniformMat4` and the other `UploadUniform*` methods each create a new `Dx11ConstantBuffer<T>` on the stack, create a `D3D11_USAGE_DEFAULT` GPU buffer, and call `VSSetConstantBuffers`. This is called once per scene begin (for `u_ViewProjection`), not per draw call, so the overhead is bounded.

### Shader layout DSL is custom
The `.shader` file format includes a `#type layout` section with a custom text DSL (`type Float3 POSITION`, etc.) rather than reflection from the HLSL. The `Dx11Shader` parser reads this section and constructs a `BufferLayout`, which is then used to build the `D3D11_INPUT_ELEMENT_DESC` array. Adding a new vertex attribute requires editing both the layout section and the HLSL input struct.

### `TEXID` vertex attribute is always 0 in practice
`QuadData` always passes `textureId = 0` to `VertexData`. The texture slot ID attribute is present in the vertex layout and shader inputs but is unused in the pixel shader logic (which samples a single `Texture2D` bound to slot 0). The field exists as scaffolding for a future multi-texture binding approach.

### Testing API selected at compile time
`RendererAPI::s_API` and `RenderCommand::s_RendererAPI` are initialised to `Testing` when the `TESTS_ENABLED` preprocessor flag is set (the `Testing` CMake configuration). The `Testing` implementations record calls without issuing any GPU commands, enabling unit tests to run without a GPU or window.

### `Dx11Texture2DArray` is a stub
All three methods (`Dx11Texture2DArray` constructor, `Append`, `Bind`) assert `NOT IMPLEMENTED`. The abstract `Texture2DArray` interface exists in the codebase but has no working implementation.

### Y-axis direction
The engine uses a coordinate system where Y increases upward. DirectX NDC has Y increasing downward. The `VertexData` constructor negates the Y position when `Texture2D::FlipY()` is true (DirectX 11 build), transparently converting between the two conventions so all higher-level code operates in the engine's native coordinate space.
